  "notes": "Standard Italian (based on Florentine/Tuscan). Open/close mid-vowel distinction (e/ɛ, o/ɔ) is lexically determined and varies by region. Gemination is phonemic (fato/fatto). Gorgia toscana (intervocalic stop aspiration) is a regional Tuscan feature, not standard. C/G SOFTENING: c→[tʃ] and g→[dʒ] before e/i (ci, ce, gi, ge); [k]/[ɡ] elsewhere. INTERVOCALIC s: [z] between vowels in standard Italian (N. Italy); [s] word-initially. Z: [dz] word-initially and post-consonantally, [ts] in other positions. SC: [ʃ] before e/i, [sk] elsewhere. Sources: Lepschy & Lepschy (1988), Maiden (1995), Rogers & d'Arcangeli (2004).",
  "quality": "research",
